# Commit messages

When the user asks for a commit title, description, or what to write in a commit:

- Always provide **type**, **title**, and **description**
- Follow conventional commits (`feat`, `fix`, `chore`, etc.)
- Title: concise, focuses on why — **without** the type prefix (`feat:`, `chore:`, …)
- Description: 1–2 short sentences explaining the why/impact, without listing files
- Write the description so it can be pasted straight into the terminal (e.g. a `git commit` HEREDOC): plain text only, no markdown, and prefer a single continuous line
- Present title and description in **separate copyable code blocks**
- Introduce the type in natural language, with a short reason — not as part of the title block

## Format to use in chat

O commit deveria ser um **chore**, porque só ajusta o carregamento de env local, sem mudar comportamento de produto.

**Título**

```
support local env overrides via .env.*.local
```

**Descrição**

```
Load .env.{NODE_ENV}.local after the base env file so local secrets can override shared defaults without changing committed env files.
```

When actually creating the git commit (via `git commit`), join them as `type: title` plus the description body.
